@Andrzej  and Francis

This is kind of funny to me because from my life experience, I never thought of gamers as toxic masculinity or anything negative. Like, in high school when I became aware that there were people more than just casually interested in an occasional video game, they were the funny, sweet, super smart set, who were considered nerdy.... people I was much more likely to hang out with.  The jock labeled guys were the ones who seemed to have toxic masculinity. I wanted nothing to do with them, which was convenient because I was not there sort either.

So, to me a gamer is kind of endearing. In fact, my boss, who is a young '30s female, and her very lovely husband are super into gaming. As such, I've kind of been learning more about the world of gaming, which has been interesting. Just the other day she mentioned some social media things in a meeting, and she included Twitch...  Never heard of it!  Turns out, it's a social media kind of thing where you watch other people game. That kind of blows my mind!

@Byron

Right? I pwned in online FPS games when I was 20, headshotting opponents across the whole map with my bolt action rifle. Already at 35 I could not keep up with youngsters. If I play an FPS these days in my mid 40s, it's something like Borderlands, single player only, and where accuracy is not as important.

I liked most AC games. Especially AC Odyssey was incredible, but I have a thing for ancient Mediterranean history. Visiting a thriving, living ancient Greece at the height of the classical era - which for the most part was very well recreated - was a dream come true for me.

@HeathieJ 

I loved the original game and I would never watch the show. The game was perfect in its world building, pacing of the story, immersion provided by being an interactive experience. When I finished it, I was deeply moved, and the feeling stayed with me for days. I just can't risk a series adaptation spoiling my memories of that exceptional story as told in the game. I also never played part 2 of the game, having seen the disgusting sadism of its first trailer.

@Andrzej 

I hear you about the experience of visiting a historical world you find fascinating. That was the best part about the Ezio story for me: being able to explore the Duomo and Florence in general, ancient Rome including the Colosseum, Venezia, San Gimignano‚Ä¶ I found the real world enhanced the game as much as theme enhanced the real world. Quite something. One specific tourist experience that was much enlivened by playing the game was visiting the weapon exhibit in a museum in Italy (I forget which one) where every single weapon in the game was displayed! Very cool!

I haven't been to Greece so don't have quite the same feel there.

@Byron 

The thing is, the Italian monuments are still all there - climbing the Firenze duomo as Ezio was cool, but I went up to its dome in real life, too (albeit not as acrobatically), so there wasn't really anything special about the in-game world. With Greece it's completely different - almost nothing survives there from the classical era, except for much of the Acropolis of Athens. Don't get me wrong, I felt special things when when I saw the ruins of Sparta or Argos bathed in the soft sunlight of early spring, with flowers blooming among the crumbling marble blocks, but to actually walk among the temples of Olympia and the treasuries of Delphi, to watch the Acropolis of Corinth from the deck of my ship... Wow, just wow. 

The creators of the game took some liberties, obviously, like making the statue of Athena on the Athens Acropolis some 3 times larger than it was, building a grandiose version of the palace at Knossos and sculpting a gargantuan statue of Artemis on Delos, but 95% of what they did was true to history. Amazing stuff.

